A fantastic simulation game, the one that started Kairosoft's fame (in the US, at least)! Having played it again recently, I do notice that it shows its age in a few ways. Gameplay gets repetitive after year 15 or so (depending on the player's skill level), and once a certain amount of capital is acquired it becomes nearly impossible to lose (or get better either). That said, Kairosoft definitely hit an excellent formula here that only gets better in their later titles!

Really great game. An organic and addicting gameplay loop, generally deep progression and only a SLIGHT misunderstandings of how the gaming market works. It's a solid 7.5/10, so I'll give it 4 stars. Recommended, even if you need to pay.

I really enjoy the concept of this game - what im not a fan of is having such a small selection of possible employees, and then needing to make sure to have the right specific employees trained up specifically the right way in order to make the best games. It feels very limiting, and once I found out that I cant just build my team how I want, and with enough training make truly great games - I HAVE to get specific characters and train them in a specific way, I pretty much lost all interest.

Simple to learn and a lot of fun, but it gets too easy after a while. The story timeline is 20 years (about 6hrs if you play straight through), and the first 10 years is exciting and challenging with new consoles being released at a frenetic pace, forcing you to carefully consider your budget and market share of each platform. But after 10yrs everything slows down and if you figured out 1 or 2 successful genres you can just release sequels continuously and get the same returns every time.

Extremely addictive but lack content and customization. In the somewhat 
early part of the game, it was very interesting and very addictive. New 
game consoles were being put out in the market by the month and older 
consoles were being taken off shelves, which forced players to get 
licensing to develop games for new consoles if they wanted to stay 
relevant. It was great. But then the story just stopped at the 20th year 
in-game. 20 years might seem like a long time to you, but when one week 
passes by in literally seconds in the game, 20 years suddenly isn't alot of 
time, especially for a game that's supposed to keep you hooked on hours on 
end. Sure you get events like Gamedex and video game awards every once in a 
while, but it's just not a challenge anymore. After the 20th year, all 
that's really left to do is to just try to beat your previous sale unit 
record. The next issue is that why are there only 3 offices? Alot of gaming 
empires like Blizzard have humongous headquarters, why are we limited to 
one floor of a building with 8 employee positions? We could have had 300 
thousand employees, and produce games by the minute. Third issue is the 
lack of customization. What you see is what you get. You don't get to paint 
the walls or the floors of the office. You don't get to replace windows or 
doors, or even put in new decor. You don't get to buy new chairs so your 
employees are more comfortable during work. But most importantly, you don't 
get to buy new equipment so game development can happen faster. You don't 
know how many times I've lost precious game points because of equipment 
failure. This wouldn't be a problem if I could just upgrade everything. My 
company sure has the money to do it, so why isn't that an option? It was a 
great game, with great potential and great gameplay at the start. Price is 
too expensive for only a few hours of fun.

Too short sighted. Aside from ming games hilarious things and still getting almost perfect scores (Grindr Friends, an action RPG dungeon type game), I got far enough where I have so much excess money but nothing to do with it. The option to make my own console just appeared after some time, but the type of person needed to hire, a hardware engineer, wasn't available to hire or even change jobs to that choice. The game awards are kind of a joke, I made the best selling game of the year multiple times and lost out to a game that didn't win any award, it was all randomized, or at least that's the vibe I got as two or three years in a row the same game won.   With that said, here's what I think would make the game more engaging;  1. Accurate console use percentages and numbers. ..How can I have only two thousand fans but my games sell 5 million copies continuously? Why does the PC have 1% of the market 5 years in when it remains and has remained a benchmarking tool for what games can graphically accomplish?   2. More office choices, perhaps add decor to be able to make your space to make games your own. Only three offices to choose from that I saw.  3. Make hardware engineers available so you're able to make your own consoles. Maybe even be able to self publish your games to save cost.  4. Have more than three people review your game, the world is a big place. I find it hilarious that despite having multiple games getting the "Hall of Fame" the chances of being featured in "a major magazine" or a segment of a TV show still completely random.  Other than the complaints I listed I liked the game, I did, but I don't think I'll play again until more replayability is built into it.

To get a hardware engineer you will need to hire someone that jobs can be changed to every job, including hardware engineer. You will not be able to change career to hardware engineer yet. You need to change the member of staffs job to every job in the game eg. Producer, sound engineer etc. You will need to make sure he/she is lvl 5 on every job. Once he/she is lvl 5 on every job you will be able to change career to hardware engineer. If this helped please rate it helpful :).

Lots of fun. Some hints. Create first games for PC using the Research method which gives lots of Upgrade ability. Hire a Sound Engineer and Designer. Save Research Points to Upgrade those staff to LVL5. In new 6 seat  office, hire Mr X through Open House hire - he has best power. There are number of quirks that make me wish the actual developers spent more time on their own debugging process:  "I'm doing the graphics/soundtrack/etc again? I'm not sure I can give this one my best..." What? Why cant my max level employee can't perform their specialized task more that twice a year? Do I fire them? There is no explanation as to why. And then following that, they still manage to ask for more money to improve the stat that they just told me they couldn't perform at.  There was no way to know in advance when salaries would be. You would think Month 1 of a new year, but nope. Definitely would not have spent money on development of a new game if I had known that.  Game titles are limited to 14 characters, but the form field allows for far more. Yet many of the games in the annual competition exceed that limit. I checked the option and noticed two graphics options of 'Performance' and 'Graphics.' I assumed with a capable device as a Nexus 7 that I would have no issues turning the graphics option on. It seems that the engine itself is designed to run incredibly slow on any device under that option because it slows down to slideshow frame rates and becomes irritatingly unplayable. That is incredibly disappointing given the graphical prowess of the Nexus 7. I understand the charm of the 8-bit design, but I'd love to sharpen the graphics with the available option and play it as such. Until the 'Graphics' option is just as playable as the 'Performance' option is, my rating stands at 3.5 stars.

I love business simulators! I have ever since I first experienced Transport Tycoon on PC back in the early 90s. Lately, most platforms (including PC) have been lacking good business simulators. Well luckily we have Kairosoft! Easy to play, but so fun and enthralling! Some things may be a tad confusing at first, but the game does a good job of making things clear, and you generally aren't too penalized for mistakes.   A couple of things I'd like changed or improved: - Longer game titles (Purely asthetic) - Control over when you upgrade to a new office. Have it be an option you have to pay to upgrade too. - More gesture support  Otherwise, easily one of my favorite games on android, and one of the few I was willing to pay for!

This game is a pile of BS.  The graphics and names of things are cute. The theme is great, especially for anyone who has ever dreamed of making games. It is fun to go through and unlock all the hidden genres and types of games you can make and to try and make games with them. It is fun to play with the idea of making your own video game consoles. It is fun to build a company and watch it and its employees grow from small 2-4-person startup to a big.. 8-person behemoth.  However, there is very little actual skill involved with playing the game, and what skill is involved is protracted over such a long period of time that it takes literally a full day (or more) of REAL LIFE to actually "play" this game.   Everything else that happens in the game is totally random and there is nothing you can really do to have any influence or control over it, except in some cases to cheat by saving and reloading.  Every once in a while, the game decides to randomly crap on you in the form of a "blackout" or "equipment failure" at the end of a game's development. Nothing can be done to prevent or recover from these. They're just a big piles of "f--- you". So, thanks, game.  Same to you, buddy.

This game will hook you, and for a long time. It has pleasing sprite-based graphics in a style rarely seen on this platform at this point, and it is based on a concept familiar to gamers: the game industry. And, truthfully, what gamer doesn't have ideas for games he'd like to see on the market? So, naturally, this game allows you to start your own development studio, making games and doing subcontracting jobs for extra cash. You could even make your own console, if you're successful enough!  The first time I played this game, I sat down and played for over 10 hours and completing my first full session of the game's main 20 years. After that, I soon started on a second playthrough. Luckily, there are NG+ benefits, allowing one to reach even further into their dreams of videogame stardom.  An addition that I really enjoy is the control pad option. I always utilize it, probably because I find it much more naturally to keep my hands at a specific place and navigate using buttons than pressing all around a touch screen. Still, the normal touch controls seemingly work just fine.
Even a year on I am easily spending hours of my life playing this game! Well worth upgrading :) GS2
